Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Roy Williams, Gabriel J. Odom, Zoran Bursac, and Mary Jo Trepka

16 July 2020

Introduction

Public understanding of science is critical in times of crisis. The following analysis was conducted to examine the trajectory of COVID-19 in Florida. For phased reopening, the White House has set guidelines for local municipalities in their “Opening Up American Again” report. In the report, it is highly suggested that:

  1. Local areas show a downward trajectory in the number of positive cases as a percent of total tests over a two-week period, and
  2. Local hospitals have capacity to handle all patients without crisis care.

The analysis begins by looking at the number of new positive cases each day and the number of total tests performed each day. The figures are presented together because as there is more testing, there are likely to be more positive test results. Therefore, the proportion of positive cases is also calculated. Given either a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive cases is the key metric to be used when looking at epidemic trajectory. It is recommended that this proportion not exceed 5%.

The data above show for each day since June 8th: the number of positive COVID-19 tests, the number of negative COVID-19 tests, and the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests to total COVID-19 tests.

Total COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of total tests over the past two months (shown on a log scale):

The average number of COVID-19 tests performed each day has increased from under 35,000 in early June to almost 100,000 currently. On average, from 07 June until 15 July, there was an increase of approximately 1711 addition tests performed each day over the previous day. This data is presented on a log scale.

Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of positive tests over the past two months:

Over the past month there has been significant increase in positive COVID-19 cases in Florida. Over the past two weeks, there has been an average increase of 242 new additional positive cases each day, per day. A high of 15299 for new positive cases was obtained on July 11th.

Positive COVID-19 Tests within the Past Two Weeks

In addition to the overall trend of positive COVID-19 tests shown above, we also show an enhanced view of the last two weeks, highlighting the stark increase in positive cases during this period of time.

Proportion of Positive Cases within Past Two Weeks

The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests for the past two weeks is:

During the 14-day period from 01 July to 15 July, there was a decrease in the proportion of positive COVID-19 cases reported in Florida. During this time, there was an average increase of -0.2% per day for new positive cases. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive tests obtained is the key metric for examining COVID-19 trajectory. The percentage of positive test results obtained has exceeded the 5% positive threshold recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO) for reopening.

Proportion of Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

These are the proportions of positive COVID-19 tests for the since the second week of June:

Overall, the proportion of positive test results out of all tests increased significantly from approximately 5% in early June. Additionally, this proportion has been consistently greater than 10% since June 22nd. This number is function of test availability and the population being tested. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, an increase in the proportion of positive tests obtained points to evidence of increased COVID-19 community spread in Florida.

COVID-19 Deaths by Day

Overall, deaths in Florida peaked in mid April. Florida, with the exceptions of Broward and Miami-Dade County, entered Phase 1 on May 8th. Deaths per day decreased until the end of May. Subsequently, the number of deaths per day in Florida has remained relatively stable and has yet to increase despite rising cases and hospitalizations. This overall decrease in deaths may be attributed to advances in the standard of care for COVID-19 and in addition to the decreasing median age of those impacted.

Note: Florida does not declare a death until a medical examiner’s report is processed. This impacts the accuracy of the most recent data over the past two to four weeks. This will be updated as deaths are added over time.

Conclusion

During the past two weeks, the number of positive COVID-19 tests obtained has increased by an average of 242 each day. Additionally, there has been a substantial increase in the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests obtained from about 5% in early June. The proportion of positive tests obtained has been consistently greater than 10% since June 25th. This evidence points to increased community spread of COVID-19 in Florida and represents a significant concern for the state.

Data Sources

Data sources are as follows:

  • COVID-19 Test Results: The number of positive and negative COVID-19 test results come from the Florida Department of Health: https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
  • COVID-19 Hospital Census: The hospitalization data is disseminated by Florida’s Agency for Health Care Administration: https://ahca.myflorida.com.
  • COVID-19 Death Linelist: This list is created and disseminated by Florida’s Department of Health. Deaths are medical examiner confirmed. https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
